  "response": "Lip sucking can be a result of various factors:\n\n1. Stress or anxiety\n- Unconscious coping mechanism\n- Self-soothing behavior\n\n2. Nervous habit\n- Similar to nail-biting or hair twirling\n- Can be a sign of restlessness or concentration\n\n3. Dry lips\n- Trying to moisturize lips\n- Temporary relief from dryness or chapping\n\n4. Psychological factors\n- Possible manifestation of mild obsessive-compulsive tendencies\n- Potential sign of underlying tension or emotional state\n\n5. Physical reasons\n- Misaligned teeth\n- Jaw tension\n- Potential neurological condition\n\n6. Potential medical considerations\n- Could be a form of body-focused repetitive behavior\n- Might indicate mild sensory processing issue\n\nThis habit is relatively common, but frequency and intensity vary. If it:\n- Becomes excessive\n- Causes lip damage\n- Interferes with daily life\n- Feels uncontrollable\n\nConsider:\n- Consulting a mental health professional\n- Practicing stress management techniques\n- Using lip balm\n- Being mindful of the behavior\n\nA healthcare professional can provide personalized insight into your specific situation.",
